Augochlora pura is a solitary sweat bee found primarily in the Eastern United States. It is known for its bright green color and its tendency to forage on a variety of plants. Inhabiting rotting logs, this bee can produce up to three generations per year. Both males and females have been observed licking sweat from human skin, most likely seeking salt Augochlora pura does not have a common name, but about it has been written that "...it does not seem to need one with such a musical scientific designation that means 'pure golden green.'"